<div id="review_134195467" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/134195467" />
    <a title="Janet" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4474017-janet"><img alt="Janet" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1612196917p2/4474017.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/134195467?book_show_action=true">Dec 08, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Janet" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Janet" href="/user/show/4474017-janet">Janet</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer134195467" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer13414885202361906456">This book started with an interesting premise, weaving in the myths of greece in a tale of real lives, but soemthing wasn&apos;t working for me. I got about half way through the book before I figured it out. The main character, and all the charachters, actually, are not logical, in that the author makes them do things and have reactions that aren&apos;t true to their characters, just to move the story along. They don&apos;t stay true to how she originally portrays them to be and it makes it confusing for the r</span>
  <span id="freeText13414885202361906456" style="display:none">This book started with an interesting premise, weaving in the myths of greece in a tale of real lives, but soemthing wasn't working for me. I got about half way through the book before I figured it out. The main character, and all the charachters, actually, are not logical, in that the author makes them do things and have reactions that aren't true to their characters, just to move the story along. They don't stay true to how she originally portrays them to be and it makes it confusing for the reader. It may be a reflection of the fact that she wanted them to be really human, and sure, humans are full of contridictions, but she gave us no motivations for why the characters were acting so bi-polar, and it started to wear on me. Also the book was written in third person from the point of view of Kassandra, but there were a number of times when the point of view shifted and it was obvious that it wasn't the authors intention to have multiple points of view. Poor writing and an annoying and unreliable main character made this story a slog to get through.</span>
  <a data-text-id="13414885202361906456" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

