<span id="freeTextContainer17960910837351454422">Greek Mythology retelling with a strong but relatable female lead and a good message? Sign me up! I started reading this book two days ago and finished it today. It made me laugh, it made me cry, it made me angry and it warmed my heart. <br/>Personally I found it interesting how she portrayed the different characters everyone knows (or should know) already, as well as the supernatural part of this universe. I have recently read &apos;the song of Achilles&apos; as well, both with characterisations of him others</span>
  <span id="freeText17960910837351454422" style="display:none">Greek Mythology retelling with a strong but relatable female lead and a good message? Sign me up! I started reading this book two days ago and finished it today. It made me laugh, it made me cry, it made me angry and it warmed my heart. <br />Personally I found it interesting how she portrayed the different characters everyone knows (or should know) already, as well as the supernatural part of this universe. I have recently read 'the song of Achilles' as well, both with characterisations of him others that are way different (although everyone I have read so far seems to agree that Patroclus is a cinnamon roll and needs to be protected) and it's fascinating how, still, both appear realistic in their respective work. <br />I am hoping to find more books like these, so if anyone reads this and has any recommendations, let me know please?</span>
