<div id="review_4019123921" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4019123921" />
    <a title="Whitney" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3852854-whitney"><img alt="Whitney" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1501614008p2/3852854.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4019123921?book_show_action=true">Jul 24, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Whitney" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Whitney" href="/user/show/3852854-whitney">Whitney</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4019123921" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3257724093354543639">The epic stories of Ancient Greece. Oh, so many battles! Oh, so many men who had phenomenal &quot;friendships&quot;! Oh, so many brave ...(no?) strong, (um, no), fierce (definitely not) (what was her name again?) (wait, why do these stories even HAVE women?? Females are DISGUSTING!)<br/><br/>What I mean to say is: Marion Zimmer Bradley is such an admirable writer. She writes stories about women, and mythology, and epic tales, and she puts her readers into the very bodies of these female characters.<br/><br/>And Zimmer Bradle</span>
  <span id="freeText3257724093354543639" style="display:none">The epic stories of Ancient Greece. Oh, so many battles! Oh, so many men who had phenomenal "friendships"! Oh, so many brave ...(no?) strong, (um, no), fierce (definitely not) (what was her name again?) (wait, why do these stories even HAVE women?? Females are DISGUSTING!)<br /><br />What I mean to say is: Marion Zimmer Bradley is such an admirable writer. She writes stories about women, and mythology, and epic tales, and she puts her readers into the very bodies of these female characters.<br /><br />And Zimmer Bradley chose to write a book about Kassandra??? My takeaway feeling is the vast amount of gobsmackery I feel, regarding really how much hatred is piled upon women in these tales about Ancient Greece.<br /><br />And I like to smile at my lack of prior research, because I started reading this book, thinking "oh neat, I get to see about soothsayer and priestess life. Kassandra was a powerful oracle, right?" Ummmmmmmm, yeah, but no one cared about anything she had to say during her lifetime. And whenever Kassandra in her story went through a rough patch, I thought to myself, "Okay, it's going to get better soon for her, right?" UUuuuugggggggh.. No, it did not.</span>
  <a data-text-id="3257724093354543639" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


